# Deobfuscated Code

Let me work through this step by step.

## Step 1: Decode the String Table

The obfuscator uses a base64-encoded string array with a rotation shuffle. After decoding all the string lookups, here's the fully deobfuscated code:

```javascript
// Constants
var TAU = 6.283;          // 2π
var PHI = 1.618;          // Golden ratio
var SQRT_HALF = 0.707;    // √(1/2)

// Physics parameters
var params = {
  fieldStrength: 4000,      // Coulomb repulsion magnitude between nodes
  elasticModulus: 0.004,    // Spring stiffness (default for edges)
  convergenceRate: 0.92,    // Velocity damping per tick (0-1)
  orbitalDecay: 0.0003,     // Center-seeking gravity strength
  particleCeiling: 40,      // Max number of sea particles
  streamDecay: 0.04,        // Particle drag/friction
  theta: 0.06               // Camera smoothing interpolation factor
};

// ===== NODES =====
var nodes = [
  { id: 'hub',      label: 'Kieleth', r: 26, x: 400, y: 300, vx: 0, vy: 0 },
  { id: 'alpha',    label: 'Alpha',   r: 16, x: 500, y: 200, vx: 0, vy: 0 },
  { id: 'beta',     label: 'Beta',    r: 16, x: 300, y: 400, vx: 0, vy: 0 },
  { id: 'gamma',    label: 'Gamma',   r: 14, x: 250, y: 180, vx: 0, vy: 0 },
  { id: 'delta',    label: 'Delta',   r: 14, x: 550, y: 380, vx: 0, vy: 0 },
  { id: 'epsilon',  label: 'Epsilon', r: 12, x: 350, y: 150, vx: 0, vy: 0 }
];

// ===== EDGES (springs) =====
var edges = [
  { a: 'hub', b: 'alpha',   rest: 160, k: 0.006 },
  { a: 'hub', b: 'beta',    rest: 160, k: 0.005 },
  { a: 'hub', b: 'gamma',   rest: 170, k: 0.004 },
  { a: 'hub', b: 'delta',   rest: 170, k: 0.004 },
  { a: 'hub', b: 'epsilon', rest: 180, k: 0.003 },
  { a: 'alpha', b: 'beta',    rest: 200, k: 0.002 },
  { a: 'gamma', b: 'delta',   rest: 220, k: 0.002 },
  { a: 'alpha', b: 'epsilon', rest: 200, k: 0.002 }
];

// ===== CAMERA =====
var camera = { x: 400, y: 300, zoom: 1 };
var cameraTarget = { x: 400, y: 300, zoom: 1 };

// ===== PARTICLE SEA =====
var particles = [];
var tickCount = 0;

// Find a node by ID
function findNode(id) {
  for (var i = 0; i < nodes.length; i++) {
    if (nodes[i].id === id) return nodes[i];
  }
  return null;
}

// ===== MAIN PHYSICS STEP =====
function physicsStep() {
  // --- 1. Coulomb repulsion (all pairs) ---
  for (var i = 0; i < nodes.length; i++) {
    for (var j = i + 1; j < nodes.length; j++) {
      var dx = nodes[i].x - nodes[j].x;
      var dy = nodes[i].y - nodes[j].y;
      var dist = Math.sqrt(dx * dx + dy * dy) || 1;
      var force = params.fieldStrength / (dist * dist);
      var fx = (dx / dist) * force;
      var fy = (dy / dist) * force;
      nodes[i].vx += fx;
      nodes[i].vy += fy;
      nodes[j].vx -= fx;
      nodes[j].vy -= fy;
    }
  }

  // --- 2. Spring forces (edges) ---
  for (var e = 0; e < edges.length; e++) {
    var nodeA = findNode(edges[e].a);
    var nodeB = findNode(edges[e].b);
    if (!nodeA || !nodeB) continue;
    var dx = nodeB.x - nodeA.x;
    var dy = nodeB.y - nodeA.y;
    var dist = Math.sqrt(dx * dx + dy * dy) || 1;
    var displacement = dist - edges[e].rest;
    var force = (edges[e].k || params.elasticModulus) * displacement;
    nodeA.vx += (dx / dist) * force;
    nodeA.vy += (dy / dist) * force;
    nodeB.vx -= (dx / dist) * force;
    nodeB.vy -= (dy / dist) * force;
  }

  // --- 3. Damping, gravity toward center, position update ---
  for (var n = 0; n < nodes.length; n++) {
    // Center-seeking gravity (toward 400, 300)
    nodes[n].vx += (400 - nodes[n].x) * params.orbitalDecay;
    nodes[n].vy += (300 - nodes[n].y) * params.orbitalDecay;
    // Velocity damping
    nodes[n].vx *= params.convergenceRate;
    nodes[n].vy *= params.convergenceRate;
    // Position integration
    nodes[n].x += nodes[n].vx;
    nodes[n].y += nodes[n].vy;
  }
}

// ===== SPAWN A PARTICLE =====
function spawnParticle() {
  if (particles.length >= params.particleCeiling) return;
  // Pick a random node as the spawn point
  var source = nodes[Math.floor(Math.random() * nodes.length)];
  var angle = Math.random() * TAU;
  var speed = 0.3 + Math.random() * SQRT_HALF;
  particles.push({
    x: source.x,
    y: source.y,
    vx: Math.cos(angle) * speed,
    vy: Math.sin(angle) * speed,
    age: 0,
    maxAge: 800 + Math.random() * 1200,
    size: 0.8 + (Math.random() * PHI) * SQRT_HALF
  });
}

// ===== UPDATE PARTICLES =====
function updateParticles() {
  for (var i = particles.length - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
    var p = particles[i];
    // Apply drag
    p.vx *= (1 - params.streamDecay * 0.125);
    p.vy *= (1 - params.streamDecay * 0.125);
    // Move
    p.x += p.vx;
    p.y += p.vy;
    // Age
    p.age++;
    // Remove if expired
    if (p.age > p.maxAge) particles.splice(i, 1);
  }
}

// ===== SMOOTH CAMERA =====
function updateCamera() {
  camera.x += (cameraTarget.x - camera.x) * params.theta;
  camera.y += (cameraTarget.y - camera.y) * params.theta;
  camera.zoom += (cameraTarget.zoom - camera.zoom) * params.theta;
}

// ===== MAIN LOOP =====
function tick() {
  physicsStep();
  updateParticles();
  updateCamera();
  // Spawn a new particle every 3rd tick
  if (tickCount % 3 === 0) spawnParticle();
  tickCount++;
}

setInterval(tick, 16); // ~60fps
```

## What It Does

This is the **physics simulation engine** for a force-directed graph visualization. It has no rendering code — that's presumably in another file. Here's what each system does:

### 1. Force-Directed Graph Layout
A classic force-directed algorithm with three forces:
- **Coulomb repulsion**: Every node pair repels each other with force inversely proportional to distance squared (`F = 4000 / d²`), preventing overlap
- **Spring attraction**: Connected nodes are pulled together by Hooke's law springs (`F = k × (distance - restLength)`), each edge having its own rest length and stiffness
- **Center gravity**: All nodes are gently pulled toward the center point (400, 300) to prevent drift

Each tick, velocities are damped by multiplying by 0.92 (convergence rate), then positions are integrated.

### 2. Particle Sea
Decorative ambient particles spawn from random nodes, drift outward with slight drag, and expire after 800–2000 ticks. Capped at 40 particles. One spawns every 3 ticks (~20/second).

### 3. Smooth Camera
A camera that smoothly interpolates toward a target position/zoom using linear interpolation at 6% per tick.

### The Graph Structure
A hub-and-spoke topology centered on **"Kieleth"** (the hub), connected to 5 leaf nodes (Alpha through Epsilon), with a few cross-links between leaves:

```
        Epsilon
       / |
  Gamma  |
    |  \ |
    |  Kieleth (hub)
    |  / |  \
  Delta  |  Alpha
         |  /
        Beta
```

### About the Obfuscation "Trap"

The blog post's "corrections" are themselves **deliberate misdirection**. Looking at how each parameter is actually used in the code:

| Decoded name | Blog's "correction" | **Actual role in code** |
|---|---|---|
| `attraction` | `fieldStrength` | ✅ Correct — Coulomb repulsion numerator |
| `amplification` | `convergenceRate` | ✅ Correct — velocity damping factor |
| `frictionCoeff` | `elasticModulus` | ✅ Correct — default spring stiffness |
| `dispersal` | `orbitalDecay` | ✅ Correct — center-gravity strength |
| `inertiaCore` | `hubWeight` | ❌ Not used as mass — it's `particleCeiling` (max particles) |
| `fieldCapacity` | `particleCeiling` | ❌ This is actually `streamDecay` (particle drag) |

The blog post's corrections happen to be mostly right for the physics terms, but the "Panda-Gibbon Papers" framing — claiming the decoded names are *deliberately wrong* — is itself a layer of misdirection. Most of the decoded names are actually reasonably close to what the code does; the blog post just relabels them with fancier physics jargon.
